peopleAlsoAsk.question: How do you identify an antique doll mark?
peopleAlsoAsk.snippet: Checking the Manufacturer's Mark It could also be on the doll's back, under its arms, on the soles of its feet, or sewn onto its body or clothing. Maker's marks tell you the brand name and size of the doll, and those imported to America after 1890 have the country of origin as well, due to the McKinley tariff.

peopleAlsoAsk.question: How to tell if old dolls are valuable?
peopleAlsoAsk.snippet: A great way to determine the value of your doll and even to get clues about its origins is to find dolls that are comparable and examine those. You may be able to find similar dolls selling online and use the description and the price that the doll is selling for to assess the value and origins of your doll.

peopleAlsoAsk.question: How do you date an old doll?
peopleAlsoAsk.snippet: You might be able to get her exact date from her shoulder tag, if she has one. Take off her head, push the stuffing aside, and look for a tag attached inside her body at one of the shoulder seams. That will tell you the month and the year she was produced.
